Lambda analyzer

Run the generator loop from the repository root:

root -l -b -q analysis/loop_generators.cxx

Then make generator comparison plots:

root -l -b -q 'analysis/generator_overlay.cxx'

For one file:

root -l
root [0] .L analysis/analyser.cxx+
root [1] analyser("path/to/sample.flat.root", "sample_label").loop()

Topology yields for a generator/knob matrix:

Manifest columns:
input_flat_root<TAB>generator<TAB>knob<TAB>sample_label

example/numi/analysis/run_strangeness_topology_yield_matrix.sh path/to/manifest.tsv analysis/output/topology_yields.csv

Blank generator or knob fields are inferred from the sample label, then from the input file name.
The matrix macro also writes analysis/output/topology_yields_uncertainties.csv with statistical uncertainties from sum of weights squared and a knob-envelope systematic uncertainty for each generator and topology.

Primary mechanism study for one inclusive Lambda-topology sample:

root -l -b -q 'analysis/primary_mechanism.cxx+("path/to/inclusive.flat.root","analysis/output","sample_label","GENIE","nominal","nominal","example/numi/flux/microboone_numi_flux_5mev.root",0.0,"fhc")'

Nuclear-exit migration study for one reduced ntuple sample:

root -l -b -q 'analysis/nuclear_exit.cxx+("path/to/reduced.flat.root","analysis/output","sample_label","GENIE","nominal","example/numi/flux/microboone_numi_flux_5mev.root",0.0,"fhc")'

Use the last argument as "fhc", "rhc", or "combined". The bundled NuMI flux file exposes numu and numubar histograms; these macros use numu for fhc, numubar for rhc, and their union for combined.

Outputs:

analysis/output/lambda_analyser_<sample_label>.root
analysis/output/overlay_*.pdf
analysis/output/map_*.pdf
analysis/output/topology_yields.csv
analysis/output/topology_yields_uncertainties.csv
analysis/output/primary_mechanism_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>.root
analysis/output/primary_mechanism_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>_summary.csv
analysis/output/primary_mechanism_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>_origin_mode.csv
analysis/output/primary_mechanism_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>_raw_mode.csv
analysis/output/nuclear_exit_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>.root
analysis/output/nuclear_exit_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>_summary.csv
analysis/output/nuclear_exit_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>_migration.csv
analysis/output/nuclear_exit_<sample_label>_<beam_polarity>_raw_exit_pdg.csv

This is a first pass over NUISANCE FlatTree_VARS. It uses pdg_vert for primary strange content, final state pdg for final Lambda content, and a p plus pi-minus proxy requiring primary or final hyperon evidence for S0.

The primary mechanism macro keeps the Lambda-topology sample inclusive, then reports the selected sample by primary strange origin and generator Mode category with sample, generator, knob, beam_polarity, and statistical uncertainty columns. It first restricts all reported counts and spectra to the selected non-zero MicroBooNE NuMI flux envelope; it refuses to run if it cannot load that envelope or the sample has no Enu_true branch. If reduced topology flags such as topology_nominal_flag or fiducial_vertex_flag are not present, it falls back to a FlatTree proxy requiring final-state Lambda plus visible-proxy proton and pi-minus, and prints that caveat in the ROOT metadata and terminal output.

The nuclear-exit macro also restricts all reported counts and spectra to the selected non-zero MicroBooNE NuMI flux envelope and writes sample, generator, knob, and beam_polarity columns. It requires explicit Stage B branches such as n_exitp plus pdg_exit, or nuclear_exit_n plus nuclear_exit_pdg, and it refuses to use final-state pdg as a nuclear-exit proxy.

The detached Lambda topology still needs the reduced ntuple fields from CONTEXT: nuclear-exit strange species, Lambda decay vertex, daughter ancestry, fiducial flags, decay length, and truth-visible containment flags.
